<div class="presentation">

<div class="slide">
<h1>Emergent Semantics</h1>
<h3>Eric A. Meyer</h3>
<h4><a href="http://www.complexspiral.com/" rel="external">Complex Spiral Consulting</a></h4>
</div>

<div class="slide">
<h1>What Was That Again?</h1>
<ul class="incremental show-first">
<li>"Emergent semantics" is a fancy way of saying...
<ul class="incremental">
<li>Ground-up semantics</li>
<li>Grassroots semantics</li>
<li>Evolutionary semantics</li>
</ul>
</li>
<li>The general idea is that nobody acts as director; semantics are created ad-hoc and evolve over time</li>
<li>What we're talking about is the "lowercase semantic web", as opposed to the Semantic Web</li>
</ul>
</div>

<div class="slide">
<h1>Basic Principles</h1>
<ul>
<li>Define a <a href="http://developers.technorati.com/wiki/MicroFormats" rel="external">microformat</a> that solves a specific problem</li>
<li>Use or leverage existing XHTML markup structures to express semantics</li>
<li>Use or leverage existing standards that aren't immediately expressible in XHTML</li>
<li>A key to this approach is that semantic definitions are <em>human</em>-understandable
<ul class="incremental">
<li>"Microformats are designed for humans first, machines second"</li>
<li>In a like manner, the semantics of everything in XHTML are defined via human languages</li>
</ul></li>
</ul>
</div>

<div class="slide">
<h1>Why Take This Approach?</h1>
<blockquote>
<p>"Students no longer have to deal with muddy sneakers on the trek to McCullough - because two brand-new walking paths are crisscrossing the campus. Adding to the network of pathways that ties the college together, the concrete sidewalks were built over existing paths of dirt that the shoes of students and faculty have plowed over time."  <b>&mdash;The Middlebury Campus, 28 October 2004</b></p>
</blockquote>
<ul class="incremental">
<li>Put another way: "Pave the cow paths" <small>(<a href="http://ifindkarma.typepad.com/relax/2004/12/microformats.html" rel="external">Adam Rifkin</a>)</small></li>
<li>The semantic web is akin to evolution</li>
<li>The Semantic Web is akin to Intelligent Design</li>
</ul>
</div>

<div class="slide">
<h1>Who Can Do This?</h1>
<ul>
<li>Anyone at all, right now, today, without waiting for anyone else's approval</li>
<li>You want to identify a fairly narrowly defined problem and come up with a simple way to solve it</li>
<li>To keep standards purists (relatively) happy, a profile at a stable URI will help a lot</li>
<li>Go see Tantek's talk this afternoon to get the technical details on exactly how you can do this</li>
</ul>
</div>

<div class="slide">
<h1>Okay, How About Some Examples?</h1>
<ul class="incremental show-first">
<li><a href="http://www.google.com/googleblog/2005/01/preventing-comment-spam.html" rel="external">Google's <code>rel="nofollow"</code></a></li>
<li>Creative Commons license-link annotation</li>
<li>XHTML Friends Network (<a href="http://gmpg.org/xfn/" rel="external">XFN</a>)
<ul>
<li>Metrolling</li>
</ul>
</li>
<li><a href="http://developers.technorati.com/wiki/VoteLinks" rel="external">VoteLinks</a></li>
<li><a href="http://developers.technorati.com/wiki/hCard" rel="external">hCard</a></li>
<li><a href="http://developers.technorati.com/wiki/hCalendar" rel="external">hCalendar</a></li>
</ul>
</div>

<div class="slide">
<h1>Metrolling</h1>
<p>

</p>
<ol class="incremental">
<li>Publish a list of people you met at SXSW, with a link to each person's personal site</li>
<li>Add <code>rel="met"</code> to each link
<pre>&lt;a href="http://meyerweb.com/" 
   rel="met"&gt;Eric Meyer&lt;/a&gt;</pre>
</li>
<li>Ping rubhub.com with your site's URL</li>
<li>There is no step 4: you're done!</li>
</ol>
</div>

<div class="slide">
<h1>Success Characteristics</h1>
<ul>
<li>Solve an immediate problem or fill a need that people are already trying to address in ad-hoc ways</li>
<li>Keep the solution as simple and understandable as possible</li>
<li>"Open source" everything so that others can use and build on your work</li>
<li>New solutions just might emerge from the microformat you've created</li>
</ul>
</div>

<div class="slide">
<h1>Identity Consolidation</h1>
<ul>
<li>Use of XFN's <code>me</code> value can bring pieces of an identity together</li>
</ul>
<p class="imgcon" id="anim">
<img src="pix/mememe01.png" id="me01" alt="" />
<img src="pix/mememe02.png" alt="" id="me02" class="incremental" />
